re, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England"},"cs":{"1457–1488":"1457–1488","1458–1507":"1458–1507","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1428–1474":"1428–1474","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1488":"1488","1474":"1474","1551":"1551","1480":"1480","1507":"1507","1428":"1428","England":"Anglie","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, Anglie"},"da":{"1457–1488":"1457–1488","1458–1507":"1458–1507","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1428–1474":"1428–1474","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1488":"1488","1474":"1474","1551":"1551","1480":"1480","1507":"1507","1428":"1428","England":"England","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"1457–1488":"1457–1488","1458–1507":"1458–1507","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1428–1474":"1428–1474","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1488":"1488","1474":"1474","1551":"1551","1480":"1480","1507":"1507","1428":"1428","England":"England","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1457–1488":"1457–1488","1458–1507":"1458–1507","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1428–1474":"1428–1474","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1488":"1488","1474":"1474","1551":"1551","1480":"1480","1507":"1507","1428":"1428","England":"England","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Singleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and West Yorkshire):","habitational name from Singleton (Lancashire), probably from Old English <i>scingol</i> ‘shingle, wooden roof tile’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Bearers of this surname are said to be descended from Ughtred <i>de Sinleton</i>, holder of lands in Amounderness wapentake (Lancashire) <i>c.</i> 1160–90. This name was first recorded in Ireland in 1308 and firmly established in Louth and Monaghan during the 17th century.","habitational name from Singleton (Sussex), probably from Old English <i>sængel</i>, <i>sengel</i> ‘bundle, tuft’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Singelton","meanings":["English: variant of   Singleton  ."]},{"name":"Shingleton","meanings":["English: late medieval variant of   Singleton  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Singleton was born in 1457, in England as the son of James Singleton. He had at least 1 son with Ellen Talbot. He died in 1488, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1457–1488":"1457–1488","1458–1507":"1458–1507","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1428–1474":"1428–1474","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1488":"1488","1474":"1474","1551":"1551","1480":"1480","1507":"1507","1428":"1428","England":"England","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1457–1488":"1457–1488","1458–1507":"1458–1507","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1428–1474":"1428–1474","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1488":"1488","1474":"1474","1551":"1551","1480":"1480","1507":"1507","1428":"1428","England":"England","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1457–1488":"1457–1488","1458–1507":"1458–1507","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1428–1474":"1428–1474","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1488":"1488","1474":"1474","1551":"1551","1480":"1480","1507":"1507","1428":"1428","England":"Angleterre","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Sir William Singleton est né en 1457, à Angleterre, fils de James Singleton. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Ellen Talbot. Il est décédé en 1488, à l’âge de 31 ans."},"de":{"1457–1488":"1457–1488","1458–1507":"1458–1507","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1428–1474":"1428–1474","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1488":"1488","1474":"1474","1551":"1551","1480":"1480","1507":"1507","1428":"1428","England":"England","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","lifeSummary":"Sir William Singleton wurde 1457 in England, als Sohn von James Singleton geboren. Er hatte mit Ellen Talbot mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb 1488 im Alter von 31 Jahren."},"ht":{"1457–1488":"1457–1488","1458–1507":"